Structured diagnostic interviews—such as the Anxiety Disorders Interview Schedule-5 (ADIS-5; Brown & Barlow,
            2014
         ), the Structured Clinical Interview for DSM-5 (First et al., 
            2015
         ), Structured Diagnostic Interview for DSM-5 Anxiety, Mood, and Obsessive-Compulsive and Related Neuropsychiatric Disorders (DIAMOND; Tolin et al., 
            2018
         ), and the Mini International Neuropsychiatric Interview (MINI; Sheehan et al., 
            1998
         )—contain OCD modules that allow clinicians
            clinicians
          to obtain an accurate diagnosis of OCD according to DSM-5 criteria. For children and adolescents, the ADIS-5-Child/Parent (Silverman & Albano, 
            2024
         ), Schedule for Affective Disorders and Schizophrenia for School-Age Children-Present and Lifetime Version (K-SADS-PL; Kaufman et al., 
            1997
         ), Structured Diagnostic Interview for DSM-5 Anxiety, Mood, and Obsessive-Compulsive and Related Neuropsychiatric Disorders in Children and Adolescents (DIAMOND-KID; Tolin et al., 
            2023
         ), and MINI-Kid (Sheehan, 
            2016
         ) are available.

The Yale-Brown Obsessive-Compulsive Scale (Y-BOCS; Goodman et al.,
            1989
         ) is the gold standard instrument for assessing the presence and severity of OCD symptoms in adults. The Y-BOCS is a semi-structured, clinician-administered interview that contains two parts. The Symptom Checklist assesses the presence of a wide range of obsessions and compulsions, while the Severity Scale consists of 10 questions assessing the severity of obsessions and compulsions, each of which the clinician rates on a scale of 1–4 depending on the patient’s responses. If a patient is suspected to be under- or overreporting symptoms, the clinician uses clinical judgment to rate the item. The Children’s Y-BOCS (CY-BOCS; Scahill et al., 
            1997
         ) is the analogous measure for children ages 6–17 years. It is recommended that both the child and their caregiver(s) are interviewed together, as this allows clinicians to obtain the most accurate clinical picture, although clinician judgment should dictate this
            this
         . Second editions of the Y-BOCS (Y-BOCS-II; Storch et al., 
            2010
         ) and CY-BOCS (CY-BOCS-II; Storch et al., 
            2019
         ) have also been created to modify the severity scale item content and scoring, add avoidance into the severity scale item scoring, and expand the symptom checklist.

The Dimensional Y-BOCS (Rosario-Campos et al.,
            2006
         ) combines a patient self-report questionnaire with clinician ratings of symptom severity. Based on the patient’s questionnaire responses and the clinician’s observations while reviewing these with the patient, the clinician rates dimensional symptom severity, global symptom severity, and global impairment. The National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH) Global Obsessive Compulsive Scale (GOCS) is a single-item, clinician-rated measure of OCD symptom severity.

Self-reported measures of OCD for adults have been used as screening tools, as well as tools to gather additional information that may not be available via clinician-rated measures. These include the Y-BOCS-Self-Report (Storch et al.,
            2017
         ), the Dimensional Obsessive-Compulsive Scale (DOCS; Abramowitz et al., 
            2010
         ), the Obsessive-Compulsive Inventory-Revised (OCI-R; Foa et al., 
            2002
         ), and the Florida Obsessive-Compulsive Inventory (FOCI; Storch et al., 
            2007
         ). In recent years
            years
         , shorter versions of the OCI-R have been developed and tested with good psychometric findings (Abramovitch et al., 
            2021a
         , 
            2021b
         ), providing promise as brief screening tools.

For children and adolescents under the age of 18 years, the following child-report and parent-report measures are appropriate for assessing OCD symptom severity. The CY-BOCS-Child-Report and -Parent-Report (Storch et al., 
            2006
         ) are each 10-item questionnaires derived directly from the CY-BOCS. The OCI-Child Version (OCI-CV; Foa et al., 
            2010
         ) is a child-reported version of the OCI, which assesses symptom severity across six domains including hoarding. In light of literature suggesting that hoarding is separate from OCD, researchers developed the OCI-CV-Revised (Abramovitch et al., 
            2022a
         ), which removed the three hoarding items from the OCI-CV. The Children’s FOCI (Storch et al., 
            2009
         ) is the child-report version of the FOCI, which, like the FOCI, boasts a brief administration time of 5–10 min. The Child Obsessive-Compulsive Impact Scale (Piacentini et al., 
            2007
         ) assesses parent- and child-perceived functional impairment caused by OCD across developmentally relevant domains of life.

Additional factors related to OCD, such as level of patient insight and family accommodation, have implications for treatment response. The Brown Assessment of Beliefs Scale (BABS; Eisen et al.,
            1998
         ) is a semi-structured clinician-administered interview that assesses a patient’s level of insight into delusional beliefs. Although it was developed for a range of disorders including psychosis, it is widely used to assess insight in patients with OCD. Family accommodation, which refers to family behaviors that are intended to reduce patient’s OCD-related distress, but fuel OCD symptoms in the long term (e. g., taking on patients’ responsibilities so they can avoid OCD triggers), is also highly relevant to the assessment and treatment of OCD
            OCD
         . Data can be gathered via clinician-administered interviews (Calvocoressi et al., 
            1999
         ), parent-report on parental accommodation of child OCD (Flessner et al., 
            2011
         ), family member self-report on their accommodation of a patient’s OCD (Pinto et al., 
            2013
         ), and patient self-report on perceived family accommodation (Wu et al., 
            2016
         ).
